Rational Behind This Blog

After using R, I realized that python is sometimes better than R. Now, for simple tasks, R is still nicer because you donât have to worry about as many things (see above xkcd) and there are more built-in functions. For quick iteration and just getting it done, R is still my go-to. However, Iâve started to appreciate the fact that python is a more powerful language than R. That being said, Iâve been hearing a lot about Julia, and I want to see how it does at some of the same tasks I might do in R or python.

From what Iâve heard, Julia is nice because it is fact. It is just-in-time compiled, which is super cool itself.

Starting Simple

Plotting

Letâs begin with something simple: plotting the standard normal distribution.

using Distributions

plot(x, y)

Standard Normal Distribution

Okay, not bad. Itâs pretty much the same as R or python.

What about a histogram? Iâll try to sample from a normal distribution and plot a histogram.

histogram(x)

Histogram of Samples From a Normal Distribution

Not bad. What about a kernel density estimate? Something Iâve noticed is that installed packages takes forever because it has to compile the package on your computer.

using KernelDensity
d = kde(x)
plot(d.x, d.density)

Kernel Density Estimate of Samples From a Normal Distribution

Cool. I like the . notation for the x and density attributes, instead of the $ in R. This feels more similar to other programming languages like JS.

Right now, the Shot Made Flag is a string, but weâd like to it to be a boolean.

bb_small[!, :"Shot Made Flag"] = bb_small[!, :"Shot Made Flag"] .== "Made"

The . is known as a broadcasting operator. Itâs a way to apply a function to each element of an array. Itâs somewhat similar to the vectorized functions in R, but more explicit.

Before we move on, Iâd like to rename the columns to be shorter and without spaces.

rename!(bb_small, Dict(:"Shot Made Flag" => :made, :"Shot Type" => :type, :"X Location" => :x, :"Y Location" => :y))

Thatâs pretty nice. The ! in rename! is a convention in Julia to indicate that the function modifies the input instead of creating a new object (itâs done in place).

Before we go ahead and calulate the distance to the hoop, letâs change the type column to be a numeric: either 2 or 3.

bb_small[!, :type] .= replace.(bb_small[!, :type], "2PT Field Goal" => 2, "3PT Field Goal" => 3)

Okay, that was a lot of data cleaning! Now we can move onto something more interesting, calculating the distance to the hoop. The x and y coordinates have units \(\frac{1}{10}\) feet, and we want our result in cm (because freedom units are impossible to deal with). Letâs start with changing the units to cm.

Exploratory Data Analysis

bb_small[!, :x] = bb_small[!, :x] * 3.048
bb_small[!, :y] = bb_small[!, :y] * 3.048

With the x and y coordinates in cm, we can calculate the distance to the hoop using the Pythagorean theorem.

bb_small[!, :distance] = sqrt.(bb_small[!, :x].^2 + bb_small[!, :y].^2)
first(bb_small, 5)

Okay, hereâs our next step. First, we need to calculate the shooting percentage for each distance (aggregated to arbitrary bins). Then, we can calculate the make percentage for each group.

bb_small[!, :distance_round] = round.(bb_small[!, :distance], digits=-1) # rounding to the nearest dm (decimeter)
bb_group = groupby(bb_small, :distance_round)
bb_group = combine(bb_group, :made => mean)
first(bb_group, 5)

Letâs plot it!

plot(bb_group[!, :distance_round], bb_group[!, :made_mean], seriestype=:line)

Make Percentage vs Distance to Hoop

Wow, thatâs super cool! Recalling our goal, we wanted to see how the average number of points changes with distance. We can do this by multiplying the make percentage by the number of points for each shot. We can also get rid of the shots that are past 1000cm, because there is very little data.

bb_small = filter(row -> row[:distance] < 1000, bb_small)
bb_small[!, :points] = bb_small[!, :type] .* bb_small[!, :made]
bb_group = groupby(bb_small, :distance_round)
bb_group = combine(bb_group, :points => mean)
first(bb_group, 5)

Letâs plot it!

plot(bb_group[!, :distance_round], bb_group[!, :points_mean], seriestype=:line, xlabel="Distance to Hoop (cm)", ylabel="Average Points", title="Average Points vs Distance to Hoop")

Average Points vs Distance to Hoop

So what does that show us? Basically, if you shoot a three, you are scoring, on average, the same number of points as shooting from around one meter, which is insane! Itâs no wonder that NBA players are shooting so many threes.

Conclusion

So what did I learn? Julia is pretty similar to Python and R for exploratory data analysis. Because itâs newer, the syntax feels more natural and explicit (without being overly verbose like some other languages [cough cough Java]). Iâm excited to see how it performs with more complex tasks, like machine learning (gradient descent). Thatâll be next time!
